## Business Logic

### 1. Summary of the Account Management Service
The Account Management Service is designed to facilitate the creation, retrieval, updating, and deletion of user accounts while ensuring robust validation and messaging capabilities. It allows users to interact with a central API to manage their accounts efficiently. The service incorporates a validation mechanism to prevent duplicate account creation and ensures that only existing accounts can be modified or deleted. Additionally, it communicates with external services for account validation and utilizes asynchronous messaging for event notifications. The service is built to handle exceptions gracefully, providing appropriate responses for various scenarios.

### 2. Service Information Table

| Base Path                          | Source Repository                       | Description                                                                                       |
|------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `/accounts`                        | [GitHub Repo Link](#)                  | API for managing user accounts, including operations for creating, retrieving, updating, and deleting accounts.  |

### 3. Overall API Specification

| Endpoint         | Method | Description                        | Request Body         | Response Body          | Response Codes |
|------------------|--------|------------------------------------|----------------------|------------------------|-----------------|
| /accounts        | GET    | Retrieve all accounts              | None                 | List of Accounts       | 200             |
| /accounts        | POST   | Create a new account               | Account              | Created Account        | 201             |
| /accounts/{id}   | GET    | Retrieve an account by ID          | None                 | Account                | 200, 404        |
| /accounts/{id}   | PUT    | Update an account                  | Account              | Updated Account        | 200, 404        |
| /accounts/{id}   | DELETE | Delete an account                  | None                 | None                   | 204, 404        |

### 4. Endpoints Overview
- **GET /accounts**: Retrieves a list of all user accounts.
- **POST /accounts**: Creates a new user account.
- **GET /accounts/{id}**: Retrieves details of a specific user account by its ID.
- **PUT /accounts/{id}**: Updates an existing user account identified by its ID.
- **DELETE /accounts/{id}**: Deletes a user account identified by its ID.

This structured breakdown provides a comprehensive overview of the Account Management Service, detailing its core functionalities, endpoints, and service information.

## Plant UML script

Here is a PlantUML sequence diagram script based on the provided business logic. This script includes all key actors, main interactions, process flows, critical decision points, and highlights the endpoints involved in the account management service.

```plantuml
@startuml
actor Users as User
participant "AccountController" as Controller
participant "AccountServiceImpl" as Service
participant "AccountRepository" as Repo
participant "PostgreSQL Database" as PostgreSQL
participant "MongoDB" as MongoDB
participant "AccountFeignClient" as FeignClient
participant "Kafka Publisher" as Kafka
participant "RabbitMQ Publisher" as RabbitMQ

== User Requests Account Management ==
User -> Controller : POST /accounts\n(Account)
Controller -> Service : createAccount(Account)
Service -> Repo : check if account exists(id)
alt Account exists
    Repo --> Service : return existing account
    Service -> Controller : HTTP 409 Conflict
else Account does not exist
    Service -> PostgreSQL : save Account
    PostgreSQL --> Service : Account Created
    Service -> Kafka : publish account creation message
    Service -> RabbitMQ : publish account creation message
    Service -> Controller : HTTP 201 Created\n(Created Account)
end

== Retrieve All Accounts ==
User -> Controller : GET /accounts
Controller -> Service : getAllAccounts()
Service -> Repo : findAll()
Repo --> Service : List of Accounts
Service -> Controller : HTTP 200 OK\n(List of Accounts)

== Retrieve Account by ID ==
User -> Controller : GET /accounts/{id}
Controller -> Service : getAccountById(id)
Service -> Repo : findById(id)
alt Account found
    Repo --> Service : Account
    Service -> Controller : HTTP 200 OK\n(Account)
else Account not found
    Service -> Controller : HTTP 404 Not Found
end

== Update Account ==
User -> Controller : PUT /accounts/{id}\n(Account)
Controller -> Service : updateAccount(id, Account)
Service -> Repo : check if account exists(id)
alt Account exists
    Repo --> Service : return existing account
    Service -> PostgreSQL : update Account
    PostgreSQL --> Service : Account Updated
    Service -> Kafka : publish account update message
    Service -> RabbitMQ : publish account update message
    Service -> Controller : HTTP 200 OK\n(Updated Account)
else Account does not exist
    Service -> Controller : HTTP 404 Not Found
end

== Delete Account ==
User -> Controller : DELETE /accounts/{id}
Controller -> Service : deleteAccount(id)
Service -> Repo : check if account exists(id)
alt Account exists
    Repo --> Service : return existing account
    Service -> PostgreSQL : delete Account
    PostgreSQL --> Service : Account Deleted
    Service -> Kafka : publish account deletion message
    Service -> RabbitMQ : publish account deletion message
    Service -> Controller : HTTP 204 No Content
else Account does not exist
    Service -> Controller : HTTP 404 Not Found
end

== Account Validation ==
Service -> FeignClient : validateAccountStatus(id)
FeignClient --> Service : account status
Service -> Controller : return account status

@enduml
```

### Explanation of the Diagram:
- **Actors**: The `User` interacts with the `AccountController`, which serves as the entry point for account management requests.
- **Participants**: The `AccountServiceImpl`, `AccountRepository`, databases (PostgreSQL and MongoDB), and messaging systems (Kafka and RabbitMQ) are involved in processing requests.
- **Interactions**: The diagram showcases the process of creating, retrieving, updating, and deleting accounts, along with account validation.
- **Decision Points**: Critical checks are made to determine if an account exists before performing updates or deletions.
- **Messaging**: The script highlights the publishing of messages to Kafka and RabbitMQ for various account events.

This sequence diagram provides a comprehensive view of the interactions and processes within the account management service according to the specified business logic.

# API Documentation

## /accounts GET
Endpoint URL: /accounts  
HTTP Method: GET  
Authentication: Bearer Token Required  
Authorization: None  
Description: Retrieve all accounts from the account management service.  

### Request Parameters
| Parameter Name | Type   | Required | Description                       |
|----------------|--------|----------|-----------------------------------|
| None           | N/A    | No       | No request body required.         |

### Sample Request
```json
{}
```

### Response Parameters
| Field Name | Type   | Description                       |
|------------|--------|-----------------------------------|
| accounts   | Array  | List of account objects.          |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "accounts": [
    {
      "id": "1",
      "name": "John Doe",
      "email": "john@example.com",
      "accountNumber": "123456789",
      "accountType": "savings",
      "dob": "1990-01-01",
      "bankCode": "BANK001"
    }
  ]
}
```

### Components Involved
- AccountService
- PostgreSQL Database

### Data Mapping
| Source Field | Target Field          | Transformation                       |
|--------------|-----------------------|--------------------------------------|
| accounts     | AccountEntity         | Fetches all account records.         |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": "Unauthorized",
  "code": 401,
  "message": "You must be authenticated to access this resource."
}
```

### Root Exception Details
| Name            | Description                          | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes                |
|-----------------|-------------------------------------|----------------|--------|--------------------|----------------------|
| Unauthorized     | User is not authenticated           | N/A            | N/A    | Mandatory           | Requires valid token. |

### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message      | Description                          |
|-----------|--------------|--------------------------------------|
| 200       | OK           | Successful retrieval of accounts.    |
| 401       | Unauthorized | Authentication failed or missing.    |

## /accounts POST
Endpoint URL: /accounts  
HTTP Method: POST  
Authentication: Bearer Token Required  
Authorization: None  
Description: Create a new account in the account management service.  

### Request Parameters
| Parameter Name | Type   | Required | Description                       |
|----------------|--------|----------|-----------------------------------|
| account        | Object | Yes      | Account object to be created.     |

### Sample Request
```json
{
  "name": "Jane Doe",
  "email": "jane@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "987654321",
  "accountType": "checking",
  "dob": "1992-02-02",
  "bankCode": "BANK002"
}
```

### Response Parameters
| Field Name | Type   | Description                       |
|------------|--------|-----------------------------------|
| id         | string | Unique identifier for the account.|
| name       | string | Name of the account holder.       |
| email      | string | Email of the account holder.      |
| accountNumber | string | Account number assigned.        |
| accountType | string | Type of the account.             |
| dob        | string | Date of birth of the account holder. |
| bankCode   | string | Code of the associated bank.     |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "id": "2",
  "name": "Jane Doe",
  "email": "jane@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "987654321",
  "accountType": "checking",
  "dob": "1992-02-02",
  "bankCode": "BANK002"
}
```

### Components Involved
- AccountService
- PostgreSQL Database
- Kafka
- RabbitMQ

### Data Mapping
| Source Field | Target Field          | Transformation                       |
|--------------|-----------------------|--------------------------------------|
| account      | AccountEntity         | Converts account data for persistence. |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": "Account already exists",
  "code": 409,
  "message": "An account with the same ID already exists."
}
```

### Root Exception Details
| Name            | Description                          | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes                |
|-----------------|-------------------------------------|----------------|--------|--------------------|----------------------|
| Conflict         | Account creation conflict            | N/A            | N/A    | Mandatory           | Duplicate account ID. |

### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message               | Description                          |
|-----------|-----------------------|--------------------------------------|
| 201       | Created               | Account successfully created.        |
| 409       | Conflict              | Account with the same ID already exists. |
